<dl id="n05102g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05102g">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05102g"> 102(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> arr&ecirc;t&eacute; ministriel</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">There is a good deal of artificiality in the strict rules of the grammarians on this point <font color="green">[whether <i>gens</i> should have an adjective in the feminine or the masculine form]</font>, and it is therefore good that the <mark>Arr&ecirc;t&eacute; minist&eacute;riel</mark> of 1901 tolerates greater liberty, &hellip; <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJLN" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJLN"><cite title="source">Language: its Nature, Development and Origin</cite></a> (Jan 1922) 347</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
